A behavioral science book club of about 25 readers spread across three time zones meets quarterly to discuss a single book — recently Thinking, Fast and Slow, Misbehaving, Nudge, and Predictably Irrational — and members want a coordinated way to surface examples from the book they found striking, debate interpretations, and crowd-source the most useful concept maps. Build a community coordination app where the organizer kicks off a new book by adding the chapter list. Members can claim chapters to summarize, and for each chapter they write a short overview plus a structured list of the behavioral economics concepts the chapter foregrounds — pulling from a shared vocabulary that includes prospect theory, loss aversion, present bias, hyperbolic discounting, bounded rationality, nudge theory, framing effects, reference-dependent preferences, heuristics and biases, social preferences, endowment effect, and intertemporal choice. Each concept entry should let any member attach a real-world example they encountered (a marketing email that exploited framing effects, a government nudge that backfired, a financial product priced to exploit present bias) and link it to the relevant chapter. Other members can vote on which examples best illustrate each concept and comment with their own variants. As the book club moves through the book, the app builds a shared concept map of the whole work, navigable by concept or by chapter. At the live meeting (video link embedded), one member can drive a guided tour through the map, and the group can collaboratively annotate during discussion. After the book closes, the concept map remains as the group's permanent record, and the organizer can launch the next book with the same scaffolding.